  "prompt": "I would like to know about the common prefixes namely iso- and neo- which are used in organic nomenclature. I just wanted explanations about using these, I mean when and where to use these and what do these mean?",
  "response": "In organic chemistry, the prefixes **iso-** and **neo-** are used to denote specific structural features in the names of organic compounds. Here\u2019s an explanation of their usage and meanings:\n\n---\n\n### **1. Prefix: iso-**\n- **Meaning**: The prefix **iso-** indicates a branching in the carbon chain, specifically where a methyl group (\u2013CH\u2083) is attached to the **second carbon** of the main chain.\n- **When to use**: \n  - It is used for **alkanes** and **alkyl groups**.\n  - The main chain must have at least **four carbons** (C\u2084) for the iso- prefix to be applicable.\n- **Example**:\n  - **isobutane**: CH\u2083\u2013CH(CH\u2083)\u2013CH\u2083 (a 4-carbon chain with a methyl group on the second carbon).\n  - **isopropyl**: (CH\u2083)\u2082CH\u2013 (a 3-carbon alkyl group with a methyl group on the central carbon).\n\n---\n\n### **2. Prefix: neo-**\n- **Meaning**: The prefix **neo-** indicates a **quaternary carbon** (a carbon bonded to four other carbons) and is typically used when **two methyl groups** are attached to the **second carbon** of the main chain.\n- **When to use**:\n  - It is used for **alkanes** and **alkyl groups**.\n  - The main chain must have at least **five carbons** (C\u2085) for the neo- prefix to be applicable.\n- **Example**:\n  - **neopentane**: C(CH\u2083)\u2084 (a 5-carbon structure with four methyl groups attached to a central carbon).\n  - **neopentyl**: (CH\u2083)\u2083C\u2013CH\u2082\u2013 (a 5-carbon alkyl group with two methyl groups on the second carbon).\n\n---\n\n### Key Differences:\n- **iso-**: Indicates a single methyl group branching off the **second carbon** of the main chain.\n- **neo-**: Indicates two methyl groups branching off the **second carbon**, forming a quaternary carbon.\n\n---\n\n### Notes:\n- These prefixes are **traditional** and are not part of the **IUPAC systematic nomenclature**, but they are widely used in common names and simplified naming conventions.\n- In **systematic nomenclature**, the structure of the molecule is described using locants and substituent names rather than these prefixes.\n\nLet me know if you need further clarification or examples!",
  "temperature": 1.0,
